<item>
            <title>[THRIFT-604] nonblocking_server assumes that socket.read returns exactly one message</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/THRIFT-604</link>
                <project id="12310800" key="THRIFT">Thrift</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;The Ruby implentation of NonblockingServer assumes that each socket read places at most one message into the buffer.  A flurry of several messages on the same socket (eg, oneway methods getting called in rapid succession) enqueue the messages into the buffer, but IOManager reads only one message per cycle through the event loop.  Since select() isn&apos;t aware of messages in the buffer, this causes the queue to steadily grow and lag further and further.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Specifically, NonblockingServer::IOManager.read_connection currently has lines that read:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;gt; frame = slice_frame(@buffers&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;fd&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;)&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;gt; if frame&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;gt; ....&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;These lines should instead read:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;gt; while (frame = slice_frame!(@buffers&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;fd&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;))&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;gt; ...&lt;/p&gt;</description>
